               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1865" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1865" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1865" type="surname" value="BUTLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1865" type="given" value="THOMAS EDMUND"></interp>THOMAS EDMUND BUTLER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a linen-draper, and live at North Brix<lb></lb>ton. The prisoner had been in my service about six weeks, and was leaving me—on the 17th of Aug. her boxes were packed up, and I desired them to be opened—they were not opened in my presence, but I was by my wife's side, and heard her acknowledge that she had taken this bonnet and ribbon from my stock, that it was her first offence, and she begged I would let her go—I gave her in charge—the officer asked the prisoner to give up her key—we then went back, opened her box, and found some gloves, which correspond with some of mine, these flowers, which have my mark on, and this handkerchief, which has my wife's mark on it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHARNOCK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> This is a very common bonnet? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It is worth 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—it has my shop mark on it, which is invariably taken off when they are sold—I know this ribbon well—it is an old shopkeeper—it is a very good ribbon.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
